---

# 6ï¸âƒ£ When WOULD you need to change Case Type?

Only if:

* A **new stage** is legally required
* Lifecycle order changes
* Case closure semantics change

These are **rare** and global.

---

# 7ï¸âƒ£ Why this satisfies regulators

For any case, you can show:

* Country = DE
* Decision output = task added
* Decision version
* Task execution evidence

This is **stronger than Case Type changes**.

---

# 8ï¸âƒ£ Testing impact (important)

| Change              | Test scope             |
| ------------------- | ---------------------- |
| New DE task         | DE decision tests only |
| New task definition | Data validation        |
| Case Type change    | Global regression      |

---

# 9ï¸âƒ£ Anti-patterns to avoid

âŒ Adding assignments in Case Type
âŒ Country-specific flows
âŒ Circumstanced Case Types
âŒ Hard-coded task logic

---

# Final answer (clear)

> **You do NOT modify the Case Type to add a new EMEA task.**
> **You add data + decision logic.**

If adding a task forces you to modify the Case Type, **the design is not decision-driven**.

